{"id":"screen-rvw","title":"Compare revised PLAN_A and PLAN_B; produce PLAN_AB","description":"PLAN_A and PLAN_B look very similar to the human reader. Analyze the two (after they have been revised by the sibling beads — this task is blocked on those) and write PLAN_AB.md.\n\nStructure of PLAN_AB.md:\n\n1. Preamble answering:\n   - What are the actual differences between PLAN_A and PLAN_B?\n   - Which is best on which axis?\n   - Are they substantively different, or basically the same plan with different emphasis?\n   - Does it make sense to pick one, or fold them into a single hybrid?\n\n2. Then either:\n   (a) State the choice (A or B) with justification, and use the chosen plan's content as the body of PLAN_AB.md, OR\n   (b) Write a hybrid plan that takes the best of both.\n\nAfter writing, edit PLAN_AB.md for concision: remove duplication (both within the new doc and with what already exists in RESEARCH.md), tighten language, make it easier to scan.\n\nCommit and land PLAN_AB.md per the workflow in AGENTS.md (agent-land.sh).\n\nDependency note: this task should run after the revise-PLAN_A and revise-PLAN_B beads land, so it compares the revised plans, not the originals.\n","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"Claude","owner":"noreply@anthropic.com","created_at":"2026-04-08T06:37:07Z","created_by":"Claude","updated_at":"2026-04-09T15:24:51Z","closed_at":"2026-04-09T15:24:51Z","close_reason":"Closed","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"screen-rvw","depends_on_id":"screen-4t6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-08T06:37:10Z","created_by":"Claude","metadata":"{}"},{"issue_id":"screen-rvw","depends_on_id":"screen-cxy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-08T06:37:11Z","created_by":"Claude","metadata":"{}"}],"dependency_count":2,"dependent_count":0,"comment_count":0}
{"id":"screen-cxy","title":"Revise PLAN_B to address critiques, updated RESEARCH, and new user requirements","description":"Revise PLAN_B.md in place. Make it reflect new information and address criticism, then tighten the prose.\n\nSources to consult (read only the PLAN_B-relevant sections in the critiques):\n- RESEARCH.md — updated since PLAN_B was written, primarily with info about developer workflows that make Apple entitlements less onerous. Incorporate this into PLAN_B's entitlement/deployability discussion.\n- CRITIQUE_1.md, CRITIQUE_2.md, CRITIQUE_3.md — read ONLY the sections that reference PLAN_B. For each criticism, either defend the decision inline in the relevant section of PLAN_B, or modify the plan to adopt the critic's better idea. Integrate the response briefly into the discussion, don't append a separate rebuttal section.\n\nNew requirements from the user (must be reflected in the revised plan):\n\n1. Child devices to support today are both macOS (iMac 2017 on Ventura) and iPadOS 26 (iPad). The plan must cover enforcement on both, not iOS only. Other Macs are involved as parent/management devices — those are newer hardware running Sequoia or Tahoe, so API parity concerns that apply to the iMac do not apply to them. However, the \"always-on\" Mac that PLAN_B centers around could itself be the Ventura iMac (e.g. if it's left running in the common area); this is an option, not necessarily the case. The plan should note what capabilities or workarounds are needed if the always-on Mac is Ventura vs. Sequoia/Tahoe.\n\n2. The user is skeptical of the hybrid \"system Downtime + our app shield\" design. Their concern: UI confusion, split enforcement boundaries, and it doesn't actually reduce development work. Reconsider whether the hybrid is worth it, or whether a single enforcement regime is cleaner. Defend or drop accordingly.\n\n3. AFMT requirement is relaxed. You do NOT need to replicate Apple's exact \"request more time\" UI. The core requirement is:\n   - After an app has been shielded, the child can request more time\n   - Parent receives a real-time notification on Mac/iOS\n   - Parent picks from a few options (reject / +15m / +1h / rest-of-day, where \"rest-of-day\" means until local midnight)\n   - That choice flows back to the child device in real time and unlocks for the granted duration\n   This can be an overlapping schedule window, an override, or an orthogonal feature — author's choice.\n\n4. It should be possible for a single device to function both as a management surface and also a target. We've been talking about \"adult device\" and \"child device\", but the shielding functionality is valuable for adult devices as well. The plan should model this cleanly — management and enforcement are orthogonal roles a device can hold independently.\n\n5. The child UI session on macOS is running under a non-privileged user account.\n\nAfter the revision, edit PLAN_B.md for concision: remove duplication, tighten language, make it easier to scan.\n\nCommit and land PLAN_B.md per the workflow in AGENTS.md (agent-land.sh).\n","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"Claude","owner":"noreply@anthropic.com","created_at":"2026-04-08T06:37:02Z","created_by":"Claude","updated_at":"2026-04-09T07:40:28Z","closed_at":"2026-04-09T07:40:28Z","close_reason":"Closed","dependency_count":0,"dependent_count":1,"comment_count":0}
